Dear Sir,

Please find below the feedback for the Purchase Requisition Form. Kindly 
review and share your suggestions, if any, for the CEO’s review.

IST Review Checklist Before FSD Generation

•Confirm: What does EmpCommon = True represent? Which divisions use 
which Crystal report template?
Ans:- For multiple divisions, the employee list should be displayed 
based on division. We can continue using parameterized logic to support 
both division-wise and combined unit views.

•Confirm: Should ksp_PendPR be hard-blocking or a soft warning? Should 
it be configurable per division?
Ans:- The hard block needs to be removed, as certain critical materials 
may require immediate purchase at any time. At present, if a PR has 
already been raised, the system displays a validation stating that the 
PR is pending for PO creation.

•Confirm: Is blcode (Oracle field) required in SPINRISE?
Ans:- As per CEO Connfirmation, not required.

•Confirm: Uniqueness rule for PR line items — item code only, or item 
code + machine?
Ans:- In the PR form, certain customers associate a machine with the 
selected item for procurement purposes. This information is displayed 
based on the applicable department and is currently available only in 
the transaction print, not in other reports. This feature helps 
customers track item selection within their workflow.

•Confirm: Is po_para.PRapprovalstatus display-only, or does it gate any 
operation?
Ans:- One of the ease of use point, it display in the Transactions Form 
Side up window to know current status of the PR, otherwise every time 
qureies PR Status to know the status.

•Confirm: Is Manual PR numbering (Manual_IndNo) required in SPINRISE?
Ans:- For the controlled structure manual numbering is not required.

•Confirm: Is PurOrd.UserFooter OCX footer selector functionality 
required in SPINRISE?
Ans:- OCX (ActiveX) is Windows desktop–only. Not supported in web apps 
(browser security + architecture)

•Document: Complete list of po_para flags and their expected default 
values in SPINRISE
Ans:- Some flags are not used anywhere need to be remove from the table.

IST-A:  For the PR approval workflow — which form handles the actual 
approval action? How many approval levels are standard? Are approval 
levels customer-configurable? What happens to a PR that reaches Final 
Level Approved — does it auto-convert to a PO or does a separate PO 
creation step follow?

Ans:- The approvals are handles in the PO module also Web Approvla 
itself,


IST-B:  For the ksp_PendPR hard block — at which customer sites has this 
check caused legitimate procurement to be blocked incorrectly? Has IST 
ever had to manually bypass this check at a customer site? The answer 
determines whether it should be a configurable soft warning in SPINRISE 
rather than an unconditional hard block.

Ans:- It needs to be removed and its used in Subam only forsome control 
purpose, recently request to remove the control from the Subam Side.


IST-C:  For the Rate override from TC=1 receipts — is this the intended 
behaviour or a historical workaround? Should SPINRISE pre-fill the Rate 
from the item master (clean, predictable) or from the last receipt 
(current practice, but supplier-linked)?  This decision affects how the 
API populates the Rate field on item selection.

Ans:- TC is no where used in the PO Module, used in the Store Module 
only.

Thanks & Regards
M MuthuVel

On 2026-04-03 02:35, CEO wrote:
> Dear Mariyaiya,
> 
> I have gone through your Corrected Critical Analysis document for
> tmpPoindent.frm carefully. I am also sharing this review with Muthuvel
> before he begins the IST review, and with the full team, as several
> observations here have implications beyond the PO module.
> 
> This is a substantially improved document from the first version. Let
> me give you both a clear picture of what has improved and what still
> needs to be completed before Muthuvel can begin his IST review.
> 
> What you have done significantly better in this version
> 
> The most important improvement is the complete removal of all
> hardcoded customer ID checks. Your first version documented 13
> separate CustID blocks embedded in the form logic. This corrected
> version shows none — all conditional behaviour is now driven by
> po_para parameter flags. This is not a minor cleanup. This is a
> fundamental structural change to the form that directly improves
> SPINRISE migration readiness. The Summary Scorecard correctly shows
> 'Parameter-Driven Configuration: Good' where the previous version
> showed 'Customer Configurability: Poor'. This change alone justifies
> the time spent on stabilisation.
> 
> The dead code separation is correct and properly executed. You have
> reduced from 9,108 total lines to approximately 7,467 active code
> lines, with 27 commented blocks identified and excluded. This is
> exactly what Stage 0 required and what the v2 guide specified must
> happen before Claude submission. The analysis is now based on what the
> screen actually does, not on what it once considered doing.
> 
> The new Section 9 on External Files, Classes, and Modules is the most
> significant structural addition. You have listed 9 OCX controls with
> their GUIDs, the .frx binary resource, two class modules (clsCrystal
> and Report.ReportView), 14 global variables declared outside the form,
> five external forms and objects called, and four utility functions
> from the global module. This directly addresses the feedback raised in
> our first VB developer's mail about Common and Class module
> dependencies. This section did not exist at all in the first version.
> 
> The new Print and Report Architecture section (Section 7) documents
> both Crystal report branches controlled by the EmpCommon flag. The
> first version only noted Crystal Reports as a medium-severity issue.
> This version documents the complete branching logic, the formula
> injection for requester name, and both report objects. This is the
> level of detail the SPINRISE web API will need to generate the PDF
> equivalent correctly.
> 
> The new Critical finding on dual Oracle and SQL Server database paths
> is significant. The first version did not identify this at all. This
> corrected version shows that Oracle-specific SQL (to_char, decode,
> outer join syntax, and the blcode field) coexists in the same form
> alongside SQL Server SQL. This is a migration complexity that the team
> could not have discovered without the thorough active code analysis
> you have now done.
> 
> The validation rules are now split into six categories rather than
> four, adding Delete Validations and Print Validation as separate
> sections. The error message catalogue has grown from 17 to 25
> messages, with the additional entries being real messages that were
> missed in the first pass. The table inventory has grown from 19 to 24
> tables, all with clear purpose descriptions. The PR status lifecycle
> with all 10 states is fully documented for the first time, and the
> audit logging to LogDet_PO with all 18 fields is now on record. None
> of this was in version one.
> 
> What still needs to be completed before IST review begins
> 
> I am asking you to address the following before handing this to
> Muthuvel. Some of these are additions to the document. Some are
> process steps from the v2 guide that need to be confirmed.
> 
> 1.  Stage 0 sign-off not confirmed.  The document header says
> 'code-cleaned' which indicates Stage 0 was done. But the Screen
> Readiness Checklist (R1 through R8 from the v2 guide Section 3.2) is
> not present in the document and TL-Dev sign-off is not recorded.
> Before any FSD is submitted for IST review, the checklist must be
> completed and TL-Dev must confirm the code version is the approved
> stable version. Please add a Stage 0 sign-off block to the document
> header.
> 
> 2.  Section 6: TC Framework is missing.  The v2 FSD template requires
> this section for all transaction forms. For the PR form, the question
> is specific: does a Purchase Requisition carry a TC code? A PR
> authorises a future purchase but does not directly move stock or post
> accounting entries. If the answer is that the PR form is not a
> TC-bearing transaction, the section should be present and should state
> that explicitly — 'This form does not carry a TC value. Stock and
> accounting movements are triggered by the GRN (TC 01) when goods are
> received against the resulting PO.' This one sentence protects the
> SPINRISE developer from a wrong assumption. Do not leave the section
> absent.
> 
> 3.  Customer Variation Register is absent.  Your first document had 13
> hardcoded customer IDs. Your corrected document has removed all of
> them and replaced the behaviour with po_para flags — which is the
> correct architectural decision. But the v2 template requires a
> Customer Variation Register documenting what each former CustID
> variation was, which po_para flag now controls it, and what the
> recommended default value should be in SPINRISE. This register is the
> bridge between what the code used to do for specific customers and
> what the configuration model will do for all customers. Please create
> this register as a table in the document. It protects the IST team
> from missing a variation that a specific customer still relies on.
> 
> 4.  Stored procedure code not submitted to Claude.  Section 9.4
> correctly lists SP_GetStock, KSP_INDEDNT_CHECK, and ksp_PendPR by
> name. But the v2 guide (Step 1 and Follow-up Prompt B) requires that
> the actual SQL code of each stored procedure be submitted to Claude
> for business rule analysis. The current document documents these SPs
> only from their calling signatures — we know when they are called
> and broadly what they return, but we do not know what business rules
> are embedded inside them. For ksp_PendPR in particular, which is a
> hard-blocking unconditional check, the logic inside the SP is
> migration-critical. Please obtain the SP code from SQL Server
> Management Studio and run Follow-up Prompt B against each one. The SP
> business rules must be in Section 8.
> 
> 5.  Common module analysis is partial.  Section 9.6 lists four utility
> functions: Record_Exists, Padl, Padr, and fnmfdate. This tells us the
> function names but not what Record_Exists does internally, whether it
> handles any business logic beyond existence checking, or whether Padl
> and Padr have any edge cases. The full modCommon.bas code should be
> submitted to Claude using Follow-up Prompt A. The output belongs in
> Section 7 of the v2 FSD template.
> 
> 6.  EmpCommon = True origin must be resolved in the document.  This is
> not only an IST question — it is a developer question. The form
> reads EmpCommon but does not set it. It is set somewhere in the
> application startup or login module. The developer who understands the
> login flow must be asked: what determines EmpCommon's value at login?
> Which divisions or configurations result in True vs False? This answer
> belongs in Section 5 (Business Logic) or Section 7 (External
> Dependencies), not just as an open IST question.
> 
> 7.  Delete guard is incomplete.  V28 correctly documents that a PR
> linked to an Enquiry cannot be deleted. But what happens when a PR
> line has been partially converted to a PO? Can the PR header be
> deleted while a PO is in draft state? Can it be deleted if the PO is
> approved? These are the most common scenarios where customers attempt
> to delete a PR and get unexpected results. Muthuvel will know these
> scenarios from customer site experience. Please add this as a specific
> question in the IST section.
> 
> 8.  Approval workflow must be cross-referenced.  Section 5.7 confirms
> that PRapprovalstatus is display-only on this form and Section 5.8
> documents all 10 PR status states. But the approval process itself —
> which form handles it, how many levels, who approves — is not
> documented or even cross-referenced. In SPINRISE, the PR approval
> workflow is a separate feature that must be designed alongside this
> form. The FSD should note: 'PR approval is handled by [form name]. See
> [form name] FSD for the complete approval workflow.' This
> cross-reference is the IST team's responsibility to provide.
> 
> 9.  Rate override logic needs a plain-English statement.  Section 5.2
> notes that the Rate field is overridden by the last receipt from
> IN_TRNHEAD and IN_TRNTAIL where TC=1 and SLCODE IS NOT NULL. This is a
> business rule embedded in a SQL query. It should be stated plainly in
> Section 5: 'If a supplier-linked receipt transaction (TC 01) exists
> for this item, the Rate field is pre-filled with the last receipt rate
> rather than the item master rate.' IST must confirm: is this the
> correct intended behaviour, or is it a workaround that should not be
> carried into SPINRISE?
> 
> 10.  po_para flags — defaults required.  Your IST question 8 asks
> for the complete po_para flag list and default values. From the
> corrected document analysis, six flags are identified: BudgetQty,
> Manual_IndNo, PRapprovalstatus, Penpodetails, PendingOrderPara, and
> InditemGrp. Muthuvel must provide the answer to this directly in the
> document — not in a separate mail. The recommended default for each
> flag in a standard SPINRISE installation (new customer, no special
> requirements) must be recorded before the FSD is used for code
> generation.
> 
> A specific observation for the CEO's attention on the Oracle finding
> 
> I am flagging this separately because it is a product strategy
> question, not just a technical one. The corrected document identifies
> that Oracle-specific SQL paths exist alongside SQL Server paths in the
> same form. This was previously invisible in the codebase. If any
> current Kalpatharu customers are on the Oracle backend, that means
> their data model includes the blcode field and the Oracle-specific
> query patterns. The question of whether SPINRISE supports Oracle, or
> whether those customers will be migrated to SQL Server as part of the
> SPINRISE onboarding, needs a CEO-level decision before the canonical
> SPINRISE data model is locked. This affects not just the PR form but
> potentially every module that has similar Oracle/SQL Server branching.
> 
> For Muthuvel — three additional IST questions to add to your review
> 
> Beyond the eight questions Mariyaiya has listed, please also address:
> 
> IST-A:  For the PR approval workflow — which form handles the actual
> approval action? How many approval levels are standard? Are approval
> levels customer-configurable? What happens to a PR that reaches Final
> Level Approved — does it auto-convert to a PO or does a separate PO
> creation step follow?
> 
> IST-B:  For the ksp_PendPR hard block — at which customer sites has
> this check caused legitimate procurement to be blocked incorrectly?
> Has IST ever had to manually bypass this check at a customer site? The
> answer determines whether it should be a configurable soft warning in
> SPINRISE rather than an unconditional hard block.
> 
> IST-C:  For the Rate override from TC=1 receipts — is this the
> intended behaviour or a historical workaround? Should SPINRISE
> pre-fill the Rate from the item master (clean, predictable) or from
> the last receipt (current practice, but supplier-linked)?  This
> decision affects how the API populates the Rate field on item
> selection.
> 
> Overall assessment
> 
> This corrected version is meaningfully better than the first — not
> incrementally, but structurally. The removal of all CustID hardcoding,
> the dead code separation, the new External Dependencies section, the
> Oracle/SQL Server finding, and the expanded validation categories
> together represent exactly the kind of improvement the v2 guide was
> designed to produce. You have done the right analytical work.
> 
> The ten items above are not criticisms of the work done. They are the
> gaps that remain between where this document is now and where it needs
> to be before it can be approved and handed to the code conversion
> team. Most of them are additions, not corrections.
> 
> Complete the ten items above. Get Muthuvel's/ TL- IST review with all
